<paragraph id="AB7B3C70FF86FF8726932833FAA06433" blockId="18.[917,1311,584,608]" box="[917,1311,584,608]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">
<heading id="F0338B1CFF86FF8726932833FAA06433" box="[917,1311,584,608]" centered="true" fontSize="9" level="2" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" reason="2">
THE 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8726CB2837FBF3640C" baseAuthorityName="Hentz" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[973,1100,588,607]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="studiosus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8726CB2837FBF3640C" box="[973,1100,588,607]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">STUDIOSUS</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
GROUP – CLADE 5
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB7B3C70FF86FF872620280AFA36604D" blockId="18.[806,1423,625,1567]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">
F. O. P.- 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF872685280AFBE564D4" author="Cambridge FOP" box="[899,1114,625,647]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="313 - 424" refId="ref80693" refString="Cambridge FOP. 1902. Arachnida, Araneida and Opiliones. Biologia Centrali-Americana (London) 2: 313 - 424." type="journal article" year="1902">Cambridge (1902)</bibRefCitation>
described a variable and widespread 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8726BC28EBFBFC64F7" baseAuthorityName="Hentz" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[954,1091,655,677]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="studiosus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8726BC28EBFBFC64F7" box="[954,1091,655,677]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">A. studiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but commented that the variation could indicate several similar species (see quote at beginning of this chapter). 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8721BD28B6FA8464B0" author="Levi HW" box="[1211,1339,717,739]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="407 - 422" refId="ref83573" refString="Levi HW. 1956. The spider genera Neottiura and Anelosimus in America (Araneae: Theridiidae). Transactions of the American Microscopical Society 74: 407 - 422." type="journal article" year="1956">Levi (1956)</bibRefCitation>
agreed with F. O. P.- 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8726B12890FB286552" author="Cambridge FOP" box="[951,1175,747,769]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="313 - 424" refId="ref80693" refString="Cambridge FOP. 1902. Arachnida, Araneida and Opiliones. Biologia Centrali-Americana (London) 2: 313 - 424." type="journal article" year="1902">Cambridge’s (1902)</bibRefCitation>
previously suggested synonymies, and added 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF87215C2971FAF0654C" authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1916" box="[1114,1359,778,799]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Enoplognatha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dubia">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF87215C2971FAF0654C" box="[1114,1359,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Enoplognatha dubia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8726202952FC12656D" authorityName="Bryant" authorityYear="1948" box="[806,941,809,830]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraternus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8726202952FC12656D" box="[806,941,809,830]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">A. fraternus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species thus became even more variable and widespread, from 
<collectingCountry id="D3D37CE0FF86FF872159293CFB6C650E" box="[1119,1235,839,861]" name="Argentina" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Argentina</collectingCountry>
to northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="D3D37CE0FF86FF872620291DFC7A6528" box="[806,965,870,892]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">United States</collectingCountry>
(e.g. 
<collectingRegion id="6900F292FF86FF872104291DFB33652F" box="[1026,1164,870,892]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Washington</collectingRegion>
, DC), and from a wide range of altitudes (
<quantity id="6C3C9195FF86FF87212429FEFB2B65C9" box="[1058,1172,901,922]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" unit="m" value="2000.0" valueMax="4000.0" valueMin="0.0">0–4000 m</quantity>
) and habitats (e.g. tropical forest, temperate scrub). In a section called ‘subspecies’ 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8726B629B9FBD8658B" author="Levi HW" box="[944,1127,962,984]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="407 - 422" refId="ref83573" refString="Levi HW. 1956. The spider genera Neottiura and Anelosimus in America (Araneae: Theridiidae). Transactions of the American Microscopical Society 74: 407 - 422." type="journal article" year="1956">Levi (1956: 419)</bibRefCitation>
commented on, and illustrated, the considerable geographical variation in size and genitalic, especially palpal, morphology of his 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8726202E65FC106260" baseAuthorityName="Hentz" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[806,943,1054,1075]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="studiosus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8726202E65FC106260" box="[806,943,1054,1075]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">A. studiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Given the complexity of 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8721D02E65FAE66260" baseAuthorityName="Agnarsson" baseAuthorityYear="2004" box="[1238,1369,1054,1075]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8721D02E65FAE66260" box="[1238,1369,1054,1075]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Anelosimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxonomy, and virtual absence of behavioural data, Levi understandably preferred to treat all these taxa as one species. However, in addition to differences in morphology, recent studies indicate differences in behaviour (including different levels of sociality) and barriers to breeding (failed breeding experiments) between several geographically separated populations (
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8726282F68FC02637A" author="Brach V" box="[814,957,1299,1321]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="154 - 161" refId="ref80411" refString="Brach V. 1977. Anelosimus studiosus (Araneae: Theridiidae) and the evolution of quasisociality in theridiid spiders. Evolution 31: 154 - 161." type="journal article" year="1977">Brach, 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8726CA2F6FFBE8637A" author="Furey RE" box="[972,1111,1300,1321]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="727 - 735" refId="ref82058" refString="Furey RE. 1998. Two cooperatively social populations of the theridiid spider Anelosimus studiosus in a temperate region. Animal Behaviour 55: 727 - 735." type="journal article" year="1998">Furey, 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8721602F6FFAD8637A" author="Jones TC &amp; Parker PG" box="[1126,1383,1299,1321]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="142 - 148" refId="ref82900" refString="Jones TC, Parker PG. 2002. Delayed juvenile dispersal benefits both mother and offspring in the cooperative spider Anelosimus studiosus (Araneae: Theridiidae). Behavioral Ecology 13: 142 - 148." type="journal article" year="2002">Jones &amp; Parker, 2002</bibRefCitation>
; L. Avilés, pers. comm.). With access to much more material, and armed with new behavioural observations, it seems now that 
<bibRefCitation id="CF554181FF86FF8726E32F14FBC863D6" author="Levi HW" box="[997,1143,1391,1413]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" pagination="407 - 422" refId="ref83573" refString="Levi HW. 1956. The spider genera Neottiura and Anelosimus in America (Araneae: Theridiidae). Transactions of the American Microscopical Society 74: 407 - 422." type="journal article" year="1956">Levi’s (1956)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF8721862F0BFAB663D7" baseAuthorityName="Hentz" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[1152,1289,1391,1413]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="studiosus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8721862F0BFAB663D7" box="[1152,1289,1391,1413]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">A. studiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is rather a species complex, including at least eight species. The 
<taxonomicName id="6CC447F3FF86FF87265C2FD6FC7A6391" baseAuthorityName="Hentz" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[858,965,1453,1474]" class="Arachnida" family="Theridiidae" genus="Anelosimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="471" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="studiosus">
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF87265C2FD6FC7A6391" box="[858,965,1453,1474]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">studiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see 
<figureCitation id="33FF20F5FF86FF87214D2FD6FB256390" box="[1099,1178,1453,1475]" captionStart="Figure 59" captionStartId="133.[162,240,1879,1898]" captionTargetBox="[162,1445,200,1846]" captionTargetId="graphics-45@133.[162,1145,211,1836]" captionTargetPageId="133" captionText="Figure 59. The preferred phylogeny with informal clade names and clade numbers in circles at the nodes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5427004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5427004/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Fig. 59</figureCitation>
, clade 5) is here supported by two unambiguous synapomorphies: closely arranged sclerotized copulatory ducts (
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF8721E62F91FB4363AC" bold="true" box="[1248,1276,1514,1535]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">10</emphasis>
-1, 
<figureCitation id="33FF20F5FF86FF8720182F91FA3E6053" box="[1310,1409,1514,1536]" captionStart="Figure 44" captionStartId="118.[142,220,1724,1743]" captionTargetBox="[147,1419,204,1692]" captionTargetId="figure-112@118.[142,1422,198,1681]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="Figure 44. The ‘studiosus group’. A–E, Anelosimus elegans. A, male palp mesal; B, same ventral; C, epigynum; D, internal epigynum dorsal; E, digital photograph of male holotype. F–O, Anelosimus guacamayos. F, male palp mesal; G, same ventral; H, male palp lacking distal E fork; I, epigynum; J, epigynum, female collected with ‘forkless’ male; K, internal epigynum dorsal; L, female habitus dorsal; M, male habitus dorsal; N, female habitus ectal; O, subadult male habitus ectal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426974" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426974/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Fig. 44D</figureCitation>
), and a snout-like Eb (
<emphasis id="99B0E062FF86FF87211C2C72FB89604D" bold="true" box="[1050,1078,1545,1566]" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">75</emphasis>
-1, 
<figureCitation id="33FF20F5FF86FF87215D2C72FB62604D" box="[1115,1245,1545,1567]" captionStart="Figure 44" captionStartId="118.[142,220,1724,1743]" captionTargetBox="[147,1419,204,1692]" captionTargetId="figure-112@118.[142,1422,198,1681]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="Figure 44. The ‘studiosus group’. A–E, Anelosimus elegans. A, male palp mesal; B, same ventral; C, epigynum; D, internal epigynum dorsal; E, digital photograph of male holotype. F–O, Anelosimus guacamayos. F, male palp mesal; G, same ventral; H, male palp lacking distal E fork; I, epigynum; J, epigynum, female collected with ‘forkless’ male; K, internal epigynum dorsal; L, female habitus dorsal; M, male habitus dorsal; N, female habitus ectal; O, subadult male habitus ectal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426974" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426974/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">Figs 44A, F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="33FF20F5FF86FF8721EC2C72FAC3604D" box="[1258,1404,1545,1566]" captionStart="Figure 49" captionStartId="123.[162,240,1777,1796]" captionTargetBox="[164,1442,201,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-99@123.[162,1403,198,1720]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Figure 49. The studiosus group. A–F, Anelosimus studiosus. A, mesal view of male palp; B, ventral view of male palp; C, epigynum; D, internal epigynum dorsal; E, male habitus dorsal; F, female abdomen dorsal. G–J, Anelosimus pantanal. G, male palp mesal; H, same ventral; I, epigynum; J, internal epigynum dorsal. K–N, Anelosimus fraternus. K, male palp (holotype) mesal; L, same ventral; M, epigynum; N, internal epigynum dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5426984" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5426984/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="471">49B, H, K, L</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
